{"type":"message","id":"1cd0c96d","parentId":"82a44b52","timestamp":"2026-03-24T19:18:40.720Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, but now the wandb import in Cell 1 would get the new version too. But the error happens AFTER the cell runs, in a callback (`post_run_cell`). The callbacks are registered by the old wandb version and they persist. Even if we upgrade, the callbacks already have the wrong signature.\n\nActually, I think the issue is more subtle. Let me think about this:\n\n1. The notebook has `pip install wandb --upgrade -q` in Cell 1\n2. Cell 1 also does `import wandb`\n3. The old wandb 0.15.10 gets imported and registers callback handlers with the WRONG signature (the `_pause_backend` and `_resume_backend` take 1 positional arg but wandb SDK calls them with 2)\n\n\n4. When any cell finishes executing, the Jupyter kernel calls those registered callbacks with 2 arguments, causing the mismatch\n\nEven upgrading wandb in the same cell might not help since the old version's callbacks could already be registered before the upgrade completes. I should probably try downgrading the wandb version in the notebook instead to match what the SDK expects.","thinkingSignature":"f76518247f97ba2d4970ebea0a336bfb4a0ce9020c20d7e26cbe8ac953e1b1a6"},{"type":"text","text":"The pip upgrade in Cell 1 runs but `import wandb` still loads the old cached 0.15.10 (the callbacks register at import time). The right fix is downgrading to a compatible version:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_vbik23ap5i67_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\dev\\notebooks\\SRMoE_Training.ipynb","old_string":"subprocess.run([sys.executable, '-m', 'pip', 'install', 'numpy', 'wandb', '--upgrade', '-q'], check=True)","new_string":"subprocess.run([sys.executable, '-m', 'pip', 'install', 'numpy', 'wandb==0.16.0', '-q'], check=True)"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":51020,"output":399,"cach